         <ab>
            Hello,
            
            See below.
            On <date>7/26/2017</date>
            <time>8:51 AM</time>, <persName>Jack Bowers</persName> wrote:
            Hi Mille, 
            
            Thanks very much for the info and the worksheet you sent me yesterday, I'm still digesting it all ;-) 
            
            I've got a few hopefully not too complicated questions for whenever you have time ;-) 
            
            From the: "Mixtepec Mixtec Pronouns System"
            (1)
            - "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e41">
               <w xml:id="d1e42">kui</w>
            </seg>/ <!-- declare as free phonological variants!! -->
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e45">
               <w xml:id="d1e46">vi</w>
            </seg>" 
            I have seen "vi" in the booklets (the new "Cruxigramas" has it a lot) but what is the "kui/"?  <q> Remember that I told you there is free variation between "<seg><w>ku</w></seg>" and "<seg><w>v</w></seg>"?  Another example is: "
               
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e57">
               <w xml:id="d1e58">takua</w>
            </seg>" v/s "
               <spanGrp type="translation">
                  <span target="#d1e58" xml:lang="es">para</span>
                  <span target="#d1e58" xml:lang="es" resp="#JB">for</span>
               </spanGrp>..
               
               <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e61">
               <w xml:id="d1e62">tava</w>
            </seg>"
               
               <spanGrp type="translation">
                  <span target="#d1e61" xml:lang="es">para</span>
                  <span target="#d1e61" xml:lang="es" resp="#JB">for</span>
               </spanGrp>..
               Also "ꞌ
               <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e65">
               <w xml:id="d1e66">kue</w>
            </seg>" 
               <spanGrp type="gram">
                  <span type="pos" target="#d1e66" ana="#ART">plural</span>
                  <span type="number" target="#d1e66" ana="#PL"/>
               </spanGrp>
               v/s "
               <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e70">
                  <w xml:id="d1e71">vee</w>
            </seg>" 
               <spanGrp type="gram">
                  <span type="pos" target="#d1e71" ana="#ART">plural</span>
                  <span type="number" target="#d1e71" ana="#PL"/>
               </spanGrp>.
            </q>
            
            &gt; does that mean it sometimes occurs as "kuivi"? No.
            &gt; or does it mean it can be "kui" or "vi"? It could be "kui" or "vi" because it means the same thing.
            
            
            (2)
            You mentioned causative verbs, I haven't looked at this in a while but my initial assumption was that causative verbs are those that often start with "sn" or "xn", like "sna'a" to teach;  but you say there is a prefix so they are not inherently causative I guess.  Causative prefixes are attached to intransitive verbs to form transitive verbs.  Also causative prefixes are attached to adjectives and nouns to form transitive verbs too. 
            
            I have seen the 'tsi-' prefix that occurs in what are essentially imperfective contexts (i always used to...) is that what you mean by 'iterative'? The prefix "tsi" is habitual, but there are only a few verbs with "tsi".  The imperfective forms of the verbs express the habitual aspect in Mixtec.
            
            &gt;Could you give me a hint and an example of each the: Causative, Iterative, and Inchoative prefixes look like?
            
            Causatives The prefixes for causatives come from the verb "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e76">
               <w xml:id="d1e77" orig="saꞌa">sa'a</w>
            </seg>"
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e77" xml:lang="en">hacer</span>
            </spanGrp>.  
            
            There are sentences with the full noun "saꞌa" (I donꞌt know in which of the texts to look for this example, since I donꞌt remember which one.) 
            
            There are loan words from Spanish with the prefix
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e84">
               <m xml:id="d1e85">sa</m>‑</seg>
            like "
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e94" type="es">ganar</span>
               </spanGrp>
            <spanGrp type="gram">
               <span type="pos" target="#d1e94" ana="#V" resp="#JB"/>
               <span type="form" target="#d1e94" ana="#GLS" resp="#JB"/>
            </spanGrp>",
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e93">
                  <w xml:id="d1e94">sakanari</w>
               </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e94" xml:lang="en">to win</span>
               </spanGrp> / 
            The loan words with sa‑ that I have heard so far, different from other causatives are intransitive.  I have to record many of them to confirm this.
            
            There are verbs with the prefix 
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e102">
               <m xml:id="d1e103">s</m><pc>‑</pc>
            </seg>
            
            like, "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e107">
               <w xml:id="d1e108" orig="sasiaꞌa">sasia'a</w>
               </seg>" 
              <spanGrp type="translation">
                 <span target="#d1e108" xml:lang="en">to spread  (the word)</span>
               </spanGrp> 
            
            from "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e115">
               <w xml:id="d1e116" orig="siaꞌa">sia'a</w>
               </seg>"
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e116" type="literal" xml:lang="en">to pass</span>
               <span target="#d1e116" type="literal" xml:lang="en">transmit</span>
               </spanGrp>.
            
            The prefix sa‑ can occur with adjectives like, "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e123">
               <w xml:id="d1e124" orig="savaꞌa">sava'a</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e124" xml:lang="en">to build</span>
            </spanGrp>
            
            from "<!-- FIGURE OUT HOW TO TAG! -->
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e132">
               <w xml:id="d1e133" orig="vaꞌa">va'a</w>
            </seg>"
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e133" xml:lang="en">good</span>
            </spanGrp>;. 
            
            The prefix sa‑ can occur with nouns like, "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e140">
               <w xml:id="d1e141">satsio</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e141" xml:lang="en">to separate</span>
               <span target="#d1e141" xml:lang="en">get away from</span>
            </spanGrp>  "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e148">
               <w xml:id="d1e149">tsio</w>
            </seg>"
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e149" xml:lang="en">side</span>
            </spanGrp>;.  
            
            There are words with the prefix s‑ from sa‑ like
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e157">
               <w xml:id="d1e158">skana</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e158" xml:lang="en">to throw</span>
            </spanGrp>; 
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e165">
               <w xml:id="d1e166" orig="sniꞌi">sni'i</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e166" xml:lang="en">to make noise</span>
               <span target="#d1e166" xml:lang="en">incite</span>
            </spanGrp>;
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e175">
               <w xml:id="d1e176">stutsi</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e176" xml:lang="en">to hurt (someone)</span>
            </spanGrp>
            
            There are some verbs which have s‑ but they are intransitive like
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e184">
               <w xml:id="d1e185">skee</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e185" xml:lang="en">to harvest (corn)</span>
            </spanGrp>.
            
            Iteratives (or repetitives) it refer to events which takes place repeteadly like those verbs in Mixtec with the prefix
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e192">
               <m xml:id="d1e193">nta</m>‑</seg>. 
            
            In other Mixtec varieties this prefix is na‑.  In Mixtec this prefix has different meanings.  It describes an action which is done repeatedly, it has habitual force, and also it gives the idea that an action will start again after a certain period of time.  In Spanish is something like "
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e193" xml:lang="en">volver a</span>
             </spanGrp>" (ex. caminar).
            
            Examples of verbs with the prefix 
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e201">
               <m xml:id="d1e202">nta</m><pc>‑</pc>
            </seg> 
            are "
               <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e207">
                  <w xml:id="d1e208">ntakani</w>
               </seg>"
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e208" xml:lang="en">to tell</span>
               </spanGrp>(a story, the news); "
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e215">
                  <w xml:id="d1e216">ntakaka</w>
               </seg>"
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e216" xml:lang="en">to walk again</span>
               </spanGrp>; "
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e223">
                  <w xml:id="d1e224">ntakuatu</w>
               </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e224" xml:lang="en">to pray</span>
               <span target="#d1e224" xml:lang="en">to recite</span>
               </spanGrp>. 
            I donꞌt know the meaning of these words without the prefix but some of them come from the colonial Mixtec as barbara has mentioned before.
            
            Inchoatives are verbs derived from adjectives which indicate a change of state like the verb in English become. 
            The prefix is the verb
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e234">
               <m xml:id="d1e235">ntu</m><pc>‑</pc>
            </seg>
            which comes from <!-- find systematic way to tag! -->
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e240">
               <w xml:id="d1e241" orig="ntuꞌu">ntu'u</w>
               </seg>
            "
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e241" xml:lang="en">become</span>
               </spanGrp>". 
            
            The other prefix is "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e248">
               <m xml:id="d1e249">ku</m><pc>‑</pc>
            </seg> which come from "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e253">
                  <w xml:id="d1e254">kuu</w>
               </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e254" xml:lang="en">be</span>
               </spanGrp>. 
            
            The verbs with
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e262">
               <m xml:id="d1e263">ku</m><pc>‑</pc>
            </seg>
            
            indicate the beginning of a process<!-- find systematic way to tag! -->.  
            
            Other linguist use the word inceptive for these verbs.  They do occur in a number of languages.
            
            Some examples are:
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e269">
               <w xml:id="d1e270">ntutsaa</w>
            </seg>" 
            
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e270" xml:lang="en">to renew  (lit. to become new)</span>
               <span target="#d1e270" xml:lang="en">to renew  (lit. to become new)</span>
            </spanGrp>
            
            from<!-- find systematic way to tag! -->  "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e280">
               <w xml:id="d1e281">tsaa</w>
            </seg>" 
            
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e281" xml:lang="en">new</span>
            </spanGrp>; ,
            
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e288">
               <w xml:id="d1e289">ntuvii</w>
            </seg>" 
            (lit. 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e289" xml:lang="en" type="literal">to become clean</span>
            </spanGrp>)
            from
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e296">
               <w xml:id="d1e297">vii</w>
            </seg>
            
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e297" xml:lang="en">limpio</span>
            </spanGrp>; 
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e304">
               <w xml:id="d1e305">kukuaa</w>
            </seg>"
            (lit. 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e305" xml:lang="en" type="literal">start to go blind</span>
            </spanGrp> )
            from "
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e312">
               <w xml:id="d1e313">kuaa</w>
            </seg>" 
            
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e313" xml:lang="en">blind</span>
            </spanGrp>;
            
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e320">
               <w xml:id="d1e321">kuyachi</w>
            </seg>" 
            (lit. 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e321" xml:lang="en" type="literal">start to approach</span>
               <span target="#d1e321" xml:lang="en">to move closer</span>
            </spanGrp>
            
            from "
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e329">
               <w xml:id="d1e330">yachi</w>
            </seg>"
            
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e330" xml:lang="en">close</span>
            </spanGrp>.       
            
            A few random questions from some things I've encountered in the last few days of my annotations:
            
            (3)
            - For the sentences: 'you (2sg.inf) smell good/bad' 
            
            &gt;How do you spell the verb? "va'a/kini (tsa'un or tsa'mu)" I donꞌt know.  Perhaps, "
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e337" resp="#MN">
               <w xml:id="d1e338">kini</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e340" orig="tsaꞌun">tsa'un</w>
            </seg>".
            
            "tsa'un" or "tsa'mu" the pronunciations are like in between the two, one is [tsaɁmũ] the other is [tsaɁõ]
            
            
            I am annotating the "Cruxigramms" document recently published by you colleagues, and I was hoping you could help me figure out a couple examples.
            
            (4)
            If you are familiar with the document it is just basically hints for the vocabulary word;
            This one is from the "Kue Kiti" page and the hint is the following:
            
            "<seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e343" xml:base="">
               <w xml:id="d1e344">Tsitu</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e346">na</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e348">ti</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e350">nuu</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e352">ñu'ú</w>
            </seg>"
            
            &gt; Why is the "na" and "ti" both used? 
            
            &gt;&gt;Would "kueti" be a valid alternative to using these two separately? No. This sentence means, "
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e343" xml:lang="en">They plow with the animals (oxen)</span>
            </spanGrp>" 
            
            The sentence shows the pronoun "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e359">
               <w xml:id="d1e360">na</w>
            </seg>" 
            
            they  and the pronoun "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e364">
               <w xml:id="d1e365">ti</w>
            </seg>" animal".  <!-- usg note on "ti" -->
            
            Even if someone is plowing (ploughing) with two bulls is fine to use the singular form for animal.
            
            (5)
            From the "Kue kui'i tsi kue ntua" page:
            
            &gt; is "
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e370">
               <w xml:id="d1e371">ntua</w>
            </seg>" 
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e371" xml:lang="en">vegetables</span>
            </spanGrp>
            ? Yes. 
            
            (homograph w/ "Oaxaca" other than the capital letter right?) No, tones are different.
            
            (6)
            The sentence: "
            
            <seg xml:lang="mix" xml:id="d1e373" type="declarative">
               <w>Yee</w> <w>ña</w> <w>ntikuii</w> <w>a</w> <w>ña</w> <w>ntinchaꞌi</w>.</seg>
            Cha titsia kuu ntikuii."
            
            &gt; What is the "a" ? is that a particle/clitic referring to the object in question? The "a" means or.    Lit. means, "
            <spanGrp type="translation">
               <span target="#d1e373" type="es">Hay de color verde o de color negro.</span>
            </spanGrp>"
            
            
            Ok that's it, I'll stop there!
            
            Tatsavi'ni!  Whooops!  Remember that the pronoun "ni" shouldnꞌt be attached to the verb.
            
            Jack
